<h1>Problem 1783 - Unknown</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 7</h2>
<p>A <i>word</i> is a sequence, either finite or infinite, composed of the symbols \(0\) and \(1\), which are called <i>letters</i>. Given a word, a <i>subword</i> is a collection of consecutive letters.</p>
<p>An infinite collection of words is given: the first one has \(10\) letters, the second has \(100\) letters, the third has \(1000\), and so on. Prove that there exists an infinite word which doesn&#x27;t contain any word from the collection as a subword.</p>
